title: Ferries in Alaska. Rail in Oregon. States Dream Big on Infrastructure Funds.
content: The infrastructure bill could reshape priorities across the country, jump-starting critical projects that stalled over funding. These are some of the possibilities.

title: Sinema’s Income Tax Stance Has Democrats Looking Anew at a Carbon Tax
content: With Arizona’s iconoclastic senator cool to increased tax rates, the Senate Finance Committee is drafting a carbon dioxide fee to fund a budget bill.

title: Texas, under pressure from Trump, announces a ‘full forensic audit’ of the 2020 election in four counties.
content: The announcement came hours after the former president publicly pushed for an audit of the election results in Texas.

title: Voting rights groups sue Ohio over a Republican-controlled revision of state voting districts.
content: “Ohio may be the canary in the coal mine from what we can expect from a partisan-dominated map-drawing process,” an official with the A.C.L.U. said.

title: The U.S. has deported more than 2,000 Haitians, including some families, from a Texas camp with plans to deport more.
content: Another 3,900 Haitians are in government custody and will be deported or put into removal proceedings, according to federal officials.

title: Democrats Face Tough Choices as They Look to Shrink Safety Net Bill
content: With moderates insisting that the cost of the measure dip below $3.5 trillion, Democrats have a number of options for scaling back their plan. None of them are easy.

title: The Jan. 6 committee subpoenaed top Trump advisers, ramping up its investigation.
content: The committee is seeking information from Mark Meadows, Dan Scavino Jr., Stephen K. Bannon and Kash Patel.

title: In Biden’s Foreign Policy, Friends and Foes Claim Echoes of Trump
content: President Biden’s speech at the U.N. was a stark contrast to President Donald J. Trump’s. But it came amid complaints that some of Mr. Biden’s policy moves echoed his predecessor’s approach.

title: Secret Hearing Focuses on Hidden Microphones at Guantánamo Prison
content: Hearings resumed in the destroyer Cole bombing case after a 600-day delay caused by the pandemic.

title: As Debt Default Looms, Yellen Faces Her Biggest Test Yet
content: The Treasury secretary must wade into a standoff between Democrats and Republicans over raising the debt limit.

title: A Guide to the Twisted Thicket of Bills in Congress
content: Congress needs to fund the government and raise the debt ceiling. You’d need a flow chart to figure out all the complications, but we’re here to help.

title: Abortion Providers Ask Supreme Court for Fast Review of Texas Ban
content: The new filing asks the justices to use an unusual procedure to rule on a law that bans most abortions after six weeks and was designed to avoid judicial scrutiny.

title: House approves $1 billion for the Iron Dome as Democrats feud over Israel.
content: Progressives balked at sending military aid to a country they accuse of human rights abuses, angering centrists and Jewish lawmakers who said the United States must support a crucial ally.

title: Regulators Racing Toward First Major Rules on Cryptocurrency
content: Concerned about the potential for a digital-era bank run, the Treasury Department is working on an oversight framework for the fast-growing sector.

title: Democrats work to iron out budget differences as White House talks continue.
content: Top Democrats and the White House agreed on some proposals for financing their ambitious social safety net plan, but crucial decisions remained about its cost and what would be included.

title: A senior U.S. diplomat to Haiti resigns, citing the Biden administration’s ‘inhumane’ deportation policy.
content: The diplomat, Daniel Foote, was appointed special envoy to Haiti in July, just weeks after President Jovenel Moïse was assassinated.

title: Arizona’s criticized election review is concluding. But the copycats are just getting started.
In Push to Tax the Rich, White House Spotlights Billionaires’ Tax Rates
content: A White House analysis using an unconventional methodology says the wealthiest Americans pay far less in taxes than others.

title: With Roe Under Threat, House Plans to Vote on Bill to Counter Abortion Curbs
content: The measure has little chance of becoming law, but its consideration reflects a view among Democrats that the issue could resonate in midterm congressional elections.

title: The E.P.A. issues a regulation that will sharply reduce the use of HFCs, a powerful driver of climate change.
content: The Environmental Protection Agency is expected to issue a final regulation on Thursday morning that will slash the use of hydrofluorocarbons, widely used in air-conditioning and refrigeration.

title: For Parents ​of Disabled Children, School Mask Wars Are Particularly Wrenching
content: In Tennessee, where the governor allows families to ignore school mask mandates, some parents are making excruciating calculations each morning about whether to send their children to school.

title: National Cathedral Chooses Artist to Replace Windows Honoring Confederates
content: Kerry James Marshall will design two stained-glass windows addressing racial justice to replace a pair honoring Robert E. Lee and Stonewall Jackson.

title: Biden Huddles With Democrats as Divisions Threaten His Agenda
content: Democrats are nearing a make-or-break moment for President Biden’s agenda, with party divisions imperiling top-priority legislation and fiscal crises looming.

title: At Covid Summit, Biden Sets Ambitious Goals for Vaccinating the World
content: But his plans face a tough road as pressure grows for big pharmaceutical companies to share their vaccine technologies with poorer nations.
